If `[Union]` is added to an existing custom type, any existing pattern matching on public members of instances of the type fail to compile.

Discovered while investigating adding support for custom union types to Polly's [`Outcome<T>`](https://github.com/App-vNext/Polly/blob/main/src/Polly.Core/Outcome.TResult.cs) type which conceptually represents either the result of an operation or an exception from that operation (https://github.com/App-vNext/Polly/pull/3020).

This might be by design, rather than a bug, but there do not appear to be any documented consequences of doing so in [Union types (C# reference)](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/builtin-types/union). If it is by design, then this seems like a code-breaking change that should be documented for library implementers.

Intuitively from current behaviour, I would expect that normal pattern matching would continue to work as before on the custom type as it still has the public members being used to match, and that new union behaviours would be additive rather than replacing the behaviour. From code inspection alone (rather than looking at the type's own definition), it's not obvious that the existing type is now a union and should behave differently.

**Version Used**: .NET SDK `11.0.100-preview.2.26159.112`

**Steps to Reproduce**:

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Run the following code snippet with `dotnet run Program.cs`:

```csharp
#:property LangVersion=preview

// Remove this for the code to compile and to behave as intended
#:property DefineConstants=REPRO

using System.Runtime.CompilerServices;

var outcome = new Outcome<int>(42);

var message = outcome switch
{
    { Result: 42 } => "Success",
    _ => "Failure"
};

Console.WriteLine(message);

#if REPRO
[Union]
#endif
public readonly struct Outcome<TResult>(TResult result) : IUnion
{
    public TResult Result { get; } = result;

    public bool HasValue => true;

    public object? Value => Result;
}

namespace System.Runtime.CompilerServices
{
    public interface IUnion
    {
        object? Value { get; }
    }

    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Struct, AllowMultiple = false)]
    public sealed class UnionAttribute : Attribute;
}
```

**Diagnostic Id**:

N/A

**Expected Behavior**:

The code compiles and prints `Success` when run.

**Actual Behavior**:

Compilation fails with the following error:

```text
Program.cs(12,7): error CS0117: 'object' does not contain a definition for 'Result'
```

